{"title_page": "Harry Laurent", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Harry Laurent\n|image= Harry John Laurent VC.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Harry Laurent during the First World War\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1895|04|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place= Tarata, New Zealand\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1987|12|09|1895|04|15|df=y}}\n|death_place= [[Hastings, New Zealand]]\n|placeofburial= Servicemen's Cemetery, [[H\u0101wera]]\n|placeofburial_label= Memorial\n|allegiance= New Zealand\n|branch= [[New Zealand Military Forces]]\n|serviceyears= 1911\u20131919<br/>1939\u20131949\n|rank= [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|unit= 2nd Battalion, [[New Zealand Rifle Brigade]] (1915\u201318)\n|commands= \n|battles= [[First World War]]\n* [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]\n** [[Battle of Flers\u2013Courcelette]]\n** [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]]\n** [[First Battle of Passchendaele]]\n[[Second World War]]\n* Home Front\n|awards= [[Victoria Cross]]\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Harry John Laurent''', [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (15 April 1895 \u2013 9 December 1987) was a New Zealand recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC), the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces.\n\nBorn in Tarata, Laurent was a grocer's assistant when he volunteered in May 1915 to serve in the First World War with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] (NZEF). He was posted to the 2nd Battalion of the [[New Zealand Rifle Brigade]] and from 1916 served on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. It was on 12 September 1918, during an engagement that followed the [[Second Battle of Bapaume]], that he performed the actions that led to him being honoured with the VC. He ended the war as a [[second lieutenant]]. Discharged from the NZEF, he returned to civilian life but was recalled to active duty during the Second World War and was involved in the [[Home Guard (New Zealand)|Home Guard]]. He was the last surviving New Zealand VC winner of the First World War at the time of his death in 1987.\n\n==Early life==\nHenry John Laurent, known as Harry, was born on 15 April 1895 in Tarata, in the [[Taranaki region]] of [[New Zealand]].{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} His father, John, and mother, Mary, were farmers. His family was of French descent, his grandfather, a former officer in the French Army, having emigrated to New Zealand in 1852.<ref name=TDN>{{cite news|title=Word on the street: Laurent VC Street, Hawera|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/lifestyle/74682581/word-on-the-street-laurent-vc-street-hawera|accessdate=31 March 2018|work=Taranaki Daily News|agency=Stuff|date=3 December 2015}}</ref> The family moved to [[Hawera, New Zealand|Hawera]] while Laurent was still a child.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} He attended Hawera District High School{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} and after completing his education, he found work as a grocer's assistant. He also served with the [[Territorial Force (New Zealand)|Territorial Force]], having joined at the age of 16.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}}\n\n==First World War==\nIn May 1915, Laurent enlisted with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] (NZEF), shortly after his 20th birthday.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} An attempt to volunteer for the NZEF the previous year had been declined, as he was below the minimum age for service aboard.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sergt. Laurent, V.C.|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WT19181120.2.15.9|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Waikato Times|issue=13918|date=20 November 1918}}</ref> Posted to the 2nd Battalion of the [[New Zealand Rifle Brigade]] (NZRB), Laurent embarked for the [[Middle East]] in October 1915. He did not arrive in time to be involved in the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] and instead participated in the defence of the Suez Canal.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}\n\nIn March 1916, the Rifle Brigade was designated part of the newly formed [[New Zealand Division]] and the following month it was sent to the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]].{{sfn|McGibbon|2000a|p=366}} Laurent participated in the [[Battle of Flers\u2013Courcelette]], part of the [[Battle of the Somme|Somme Offensive]], during which he was wounded. After a period of hospital treatment, he returned to his battalion in April 1917. He received a series of promotions over the next several months,{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} and during this time, his battalion participated in the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]] as the reserve for the NZRB,{{sfn|Austin|1924|p=196}} the [[First Battle of Passchendaele]],{{sfn|Austin|1924|p=235}} and in defending the British lines near Colincamps during the [[Spring Offensive]] of late-March 1918.{{sfn|Austin|1924|pp=277\u2013282}} By September 1918 Laurent had advanced in rank to [[sergeant]].{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}\n\nDuring the [[Hundred Days Offensive]], the New Zealand Division, following the [[Second Battle of Bapaume]], was in pursuit of retreating German forces.  Leading a patrol on 12 September in the area east of [[Gouzeaucourt Wood]], France, Laurent was ordered to locate and regain contact with the German front lines.  The 12-man patrol inadvertently penetrated through the front line and located a line of artillery. Realising the patrol's mistake, Laurent organised a swift attack which resulted in the capture of 112 prisoners, with one member of the patrol being killed and three others wounded.  He then extricated his patrol, together with the prisoners, back to the New Zealand line, fighting off counterattacks along the way.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} For his bravery and leadership, he was awarded the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC).{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} The VC, instituted in 1856, was the highest gallantry award that could be bestowed on a soldier of the [[British Empire]].{{sfn|O'Shea|2000|pp=558\u2013559}} His VC was gazetted on 12 November 1918,{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} and the citation read:\n\n{{quote|For most conspicuous bravery, skill, and enterprise when during an attack he was detailed to exploit an initial success and keep in touch with the enemy. With a party of twelve he located the enemy support line very strongly held, at once charged the position, followed by his men, and completely disorganised the enemy by his sudden onslaught. In the subsequent hand-to-hand fighting which ensued he showed great resourcefulness in controlling and encouraging his men, and thirty of the enemy having been killed, the remainder surrendered, a total of one officer and 111 other ranks in all. The success of this daring venture, which caused his party four casualties only, was due to his gallantry and enterprise|''The London Gazette'', No. 31012, 19 November 1918<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31012|supp=y|page=13472|date=12 November 1918}}</ref>}}\n[[File:2nd Lt Harry Laurent.jpg|thumb|right|A portrait by [[Archibald Frank Nicoll]] of Laurent, painted in 1920]]\nLaurent was sent to England in October 1918, where he attended an [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] training school. The war had ended by the time he was commissioned in February 1919.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} He, together with three other New Zealanders who had been awarded the VC,{{#tag:ref|The other New Zealand recipients were [[James Crichton (VC)|James Crichton]], a private at the time, and Second Lieutenants [[Reginald Stanley Judson|Reginald Judson]] and [[John Gildroy Grant|John Grant]].<ref name=NZH>{{cite news|title=Four Victoria Cross Men|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190408.2.72|accessdate=7 March 2018|work=New Zealand Herald|issue=Vol. LVI, issue 13170|date=8 April 1919}}</ref>|group=Note}} received his medal from [[King George V]] in a ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 27 February 1919.<ref name=NZH/> A few months later, he left England for New Zealand and his hometown of Hawera. On his arrival, the mayor presented him a gold watch and chain, the cost of which was met by public donations.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} In October 1919, he was part of the welcoming party when fellow VC recipient and Hawera resident [[John Gildroy Grant|John Grant]] returned home.<ref name=Hawera>{{cite news|title=Lieut. Grant V.C. Welcomed Home|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/HNS19191029.2.48|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Hawera & Normanby Star|issue=LXXIV|date=29 October 1919}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nDischarged from the NZEF and placed on the Reserve of Officers,{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} Laurent settled into life in Hawera and soon found employment at a grocery store. He later worked as a sales representative.<ref name=TDN/> He married Ethel Homewood, originally from England, on 20 July 1921, in a ceremony at Hawera. Fellow VC recipients John Grant and [[Leslie Andrew]] were present, the former in the capacity of best man.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wedding: Laurent \u2013 Homewood|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/HNS19210823.2.64|accessdate=1 April 2018|work=Hawera & Normanby Star|issue=Vol. XLI, issue XLI|date=23 August 1921}}</ref> In 1937, Laurent, along with several other VC recipients, was awarded the [[King George VI Coronation Medal|coronation medal]] to commemorate the ascension of [[King George VI]] to the British throne.<ref>{{cite news|title=V.C's Honoured \u2013 Coronation Medals|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19370702.2.129|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Auckland Star|issue=155|date=2 July 1937}}</ref> \n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], Laurent was recalled to the Reserve of Officers of the [[New Zealand Military Forces]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Military Forces \u2013 Reserve of Officers|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/ODT19391107.2.88|accessdate=1 April 2018|work=Otago Daily Times|issue=23959|date=7 November 1939}}</ref> He was soon commanding a battalion in the [[Home Guard (New Zealand)|Home Guard]].{{sfn|McGibbon|2000b|p=274}} Later promoted to a temporary [[lieutenant colonel]], he was made group director of the Hawera Home Guard in early 1942.<ref>{{cite news|title=Personal Items|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/CHP19420124.2.40|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Press|issue=23545|date=24 January 1942}}</ref> Late the following year he was appointed commander of the Hawera squadron of the Air Training Corps<ref>{{cite news|title=Army Appointments|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19431217.2.30|accessdate=1 April 2018|work=Auckland Star|agency=Press Association|issue=Vol. LXXIV, issue 299|date=17 December 1943}}</ref> and held this post until 1945. He was formally seconded to the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] for a brief period as a squadron commander of 34th Air Training Squadron before ceasing active duty at the end of the war. He formally retired from the military in 1949.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}\n\nAt the age of 61, Laurent went to London in 1956 as part of the VC [[centenary]] celebrations. He attended further VC events in the following years.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} He died in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]] on 9 December 1987, the last surviving New Zealand VC winner of the First World War.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} His wife had predeceased him the previous year.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} His ashes are interred in the Memorial Wall at the Servicemen's Cemetery at H\u0101wera, his hometown.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} A street in the town is also named after him, and nearby is Grant VC Street, named for fellow VC recipient John Grant.<ref name=Kete>{{cite web|title=Grant VC Street|url=http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/taranaki_street_names/topics/show/2545-grant-vc-street-tdn-23012016|website=Kete New Plymouth|accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nLaurent's VC was displayed at the [[QEII Army Memorial Museum]] in [[Waiouru, New Zealand|Waiouru]], along with his service medals from the First and Second World Wars and his coronation medals.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} On 2 December 2007, Laurent's VC was one of nine Victoria Crosses that were among a hundred medals stolen from the museum. On 16 February 2008, New Zealand Police announced all the medals had been recovered as a result of a [[New Zealand dollar|NZ$]]300,000 reward offered by [[Michael Ashcroft, Baron Ashcroft|Michael Ashcroft]] and Tom Sturgess.<ref>{{cite web|author=NZPA|title=Medals stolen from Waiouru Army Museum recovered |publisher=nzherald|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10492853|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120907072955/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10492853|archivedate=7 September 2012|date=16 February 2008|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{portal|Biography|World War I}}\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Austin|first=Lieut.-Col W. S.|title=The Official History of the New Zealand Rifle Brigade|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-WH1-NZRi.html|year=1924|publisher=L. T. Watkins Limited|location=Wellington, New Zealand|oclc=220312361|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=Road to Victory 1918|series=[[VCs of the First World War]]|year=2014|origyear=2004|publisher=History Press|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire, United Kingdom|isbn=978-0-7509-5361-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Harper|first=Glyn|authorlink=Glyn Harper|last2=Richardson|first2=Colin|title=In the Face of the Enemy: The Complete History of the Victoria Cross and New Zealand|year=2007|publisher=HarperCollins|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=978-1-86950-650-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=McGibbon|editor-first=Ian|editorlink=Ian McGibbon|author-last=McGibbon|author-first=Ian|chapter=New Zealand Expeditionary Force|pages=364\u2013369|title=The Oxford Companion to New Zealand Military History|year=2000a|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=0-19-558376-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=McGibbon|editor-first=Ian|editorlink=Ian McGibbon|author-last=McGibbon|author-first=Ian|chapter=Laurent, Lieutenant-Colonel Harry John|page=274|title=The Oxford Companion to New Zealand Military History|year=2000b|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=0-19-558376-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=McGibbon|editor-first=Ian|editorlink=Ian McGibbon|author-last=O'Shea|author-first=Phillip|chapter=Victoria Cross|pages=558\u2013561|title=The Oxford Companion to New Zealand Military History|year=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=0-19-558376-0|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laurent, Harry John}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Army personnel]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Rifle Brigade (Earl of Liverpool's Own)]]\n[[Category:New Zealand World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Harry Laurent\n|image= Harry John Laurent VC.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Harry Laurent during the First World War\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1895|04|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place= Tarata, New Zealand\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1987|12|09|1895|04|15|df=y}}\n|death_place= [[Hastings, New Zealand]]\n|placeofburial= Servicemen's Cemetery, [[Hawera]]\n|placeofburial_label= Memorial\n|allegiance= New Zealand\n|branch= [[New Zealand Military Forces]]\n|serviceyears= 1911\u20131919<br/>1939\u20131949\n|rank= [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|unit= 2nd Battalion, [[New Zealand Rifle Brigade]] (1915\u201318)\n|commands= \n|battles= [[First World War]]\n* [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]\n** [[Battle of Flers\u2013Courcelette]]\n** [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]]\n** [[First Battle of Passchendaele]]\n[[Second World War]]\n* Home Front\n|awards= [[Victoria Cross]]\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Harry John Laurent''', [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (15 April 1895 \u2013 9 December 1987) was a New Zealand recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC), the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces. \n\nBorn in Tarata, Laurent was a grocer's assistant when he volunteered in May 1915 to serve in the First World War with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] (NZEF). He was posted to the 2nd Battalion of the [[New Zealand Rifle Brigade]] and from 1916 served on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. It was on 12 September 1918, during an engagement that followed the [[Second Battle of Bapaume]], that he performed the actions that led to him being honoured with the VC. He ended the war as a [[second lieutenant]]. Discharged from the NZEF, he returned to civilian life but was recalled to active duty during the Second World War and was involved in the [[Home Guard (New Zealand)|Home Guard]]. He was the last surviving New Zealand VC winner of the First World War at the time of his death in 1987.\n\n==Early life==\nHenry John Laurent, known as Harry, was born on 15 April 1895 in Tarata, in the [[Taranaki region]] of [[New Zealand]].{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} His father, John, and mother, Mary, were farmers. His family was of French descent, his grandfather, a former officer in the French Army, having emigrated to New Zealand in 1852.<ref name=TDN>{{cite news|title=Word on the street: Laurent VC Street, Hawera|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/lifestyle/74682581/word-on-the-street-laurent-vc-street-hawera|accessdate=31 March 2018|work=Taranaki Daily News|agency=Stuff|date=3 December 2015}}</ref> The family moved to [[Hawera, New Zealand|Hawera]] while Laurent was still a child.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} He attended Hawera District High School{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} and after completing his education, he found work as a grocer's assistant. He also served with the [[Territorial Force (New Zealand)|Territorial Force]], having joined at the age of 16.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}}\n\n==First World War==\nIn May 1915, Laurent enlisted with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] (NZEF), shortly after his 20th birthday.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} An attempt to volunteer for the NZEF the previous year had been declined, as he was below the minimum age for service aboard.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sergt. Laurent, V.C.|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WT19181120.2.15.9|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Waikato Times|issue=13918|date=20 November 1918}}</ref> Posted to the 2nd Battalion of the [[New Zealand Rifle Brigade]] (NZRB), Laurent embarked for the [[Middle East]] in October 1915. He did not arrive in time to be involved in the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] and instead participated in the defence of the Suez Canal.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}  \n\nIn March 1916, the Rifle Brigade was designated part of the newly formed [[New Zealand Division]] and the following month it was sent to the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]].{{sfn|McGibbon|2000a|p=366}} Laurent participated in the [[Battle of Flers\u2013Courcelette]], part of the [[Battle of the Somme|Somme Offensive]], during which he was wounded. After a period of hospital treatment, he returned to his battalion in April 1917. He received a series of promotions over the next several months,{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} and during this time, his battalion participated in the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]] as the reserve for the NZRB,{{sfn|Austin|1924|p=196}} the [[First Battle of Passchendaele]],{{sfn|Austin|1924|p=235}} and in defending the British lines near Colincamps during the [[Spring Offensive]] of late-March 1918.{{sfn|Austin|1924|pp=277\u2013282}} By September 1918 Laurent had advanced in rank to [[sergeant]].{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}\n\nDuring the [[Hundred Days Offensive]], the New Zealand Division, following the [[Second Battle of Bapaume]], was in pursuit of retreating German forces.  Leading a patrol on 12 September in the area east of [[Gouzeaucourt Wood]], France, Laurent was ordered to locate and regain contact with the German front lines.  The 12-man patrol inadvertently penetrated through the front line and located a line of artillery. Realising the patrol's mistake, Laurent organised a swift attack which resulted in the capture of 112 prisoners, with one member of the patrol being killed and three others wounded.  He then extricated his patrol, together with the prisoners, back to the New Zealand line, fighting off counterattacks along the way.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} For his bravery and leadership, he was awarded the [[Victoria Cross]] (VC).{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} The VC, instituted in 1856, was the highest gallantry award that could be bestowed on a soldier of the [[British Empire]].{{sfn|O'Shea|2000|pp=558\u2013559}} His VC was gazetted on 12 November 1918,{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} and the citation read:\n\n{{quote|For most conspicuous bravery, skill, and enterprise when during an attack he was detailed to exploit an initial success and keep in touch with the enemy. With a party of twelve he located the enemy support line very strongly held, at once charged the position, followed by his men, and completely disorganised the enemy by his sudden onslaught. In the subsequent hand-to-hand fighting which ensued he showed great resourcefulness in controlling and encouraging his men, and thirty of the enemy having been killed, the remainder surrendered, a total of one officer and 111 other ranks in all. The success of this daring venture, which caused his party four casualties only, was due to his gallantry and enterprise|''The London Gazette'', No. 31012, 19 November 1918<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31012|supp=y|page=13472|date=12 November 1918}}</ref>}}\n[[File:2nd Lt Harry Laurent.jpg|thumb|right|A portrait by [[Archibald Frank Nicoll]] of Laurent, painted in 1920]]\nLaurent was sent to England in October 1918, where he attended an [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] training school. The war had ended by the time he was commissioned in February 1919.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} He, together with three other New Zealanders who had been awarded the VC,{{#tag:ref|The other New Zealand recipients were [[James Crichton (VC)|James Crichton]], a private at the time, and Second Lieutenants [[Reginald Stanley Judson|Reginald Judson]] and [[John Gildroy Grant|John Grant]].<ref name=NZH>{{cite news|title=Four Victoria Cross Men|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190408.2.72|accessdate=7 March 2018|work=New Zealand Herald|issue=Vol. LVI, issue 13170|date=8 April 1919}}</ref>|group=Note}} received his medal from [[King George V]] in a ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 27 February 1919.<ref name=NZH/> A few months later, he left England for New Zealand and his hometown of Hawera. On his arrival, the mayor presented him a gold watch and chain, the cost of which was met by public donations.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} In October 1919, he was part of the welcoming party when fellow VC recipient and Hawera resident [[John Gildroy Grant|John Grant]] returned home.<ref name=Hawera>{{cite news|title=Lieut. Grant V.C. Welcomed Home|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/HNS19191029.2.48|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Hawera & Normanby Star|issue=LXXIV|date=29 October 1919}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nDischarged from the NZEF and placed on the Reserve of Officers,{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} Laurent settled into life in Hawera and soon found employment at a grocery store. He later worked as a sales representative.<ref name=TDN/> He married Ethel Homewood, originally from England, on 20 July 1921, in a ceremony at Hawera. Fellow VC recipients John Grant and [[Leslie Andrew]] were present, the former in the capacity of best man.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wedding: Laurent \u2013 Homewood|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/HNS19210823.2.64|accessdate=1 April 2018|work=Hawera & Normanby Star|issue=Vol. XLI, issue XLI|date=23 August 1921}}</ref> In 1937, Laurent, along with several other VC recipients, was awarded the [[King George VI Coronation Medal|coronation medal]] to commemorate the ascension of [[King George VI]] to the British throne.<ref>{{cite news|title=V.C's Honoured \u2013 Coronation Medals|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19370702.2.129|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Auckland Star|issue=155|date=2 July 1937}}</ref> \n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], Laurent was recalled to the Reserve of Officers of the [[New Zealand Military Forces]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Military Forces \u2013 Reserve of Officers|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/ODT19391107.2.88|accessdate=1 April 2018|work=Otago Daily Times|issue=23959|date=7 November 1939}}</ref> He was soon commanding a battalion in the [[Home Guard (New Zealand)|Home Guard]].{{sfn|McGibbon|2000b|p=274}} Later promoted to a temporary [[lieutenant colonel]], he was made group director of the Hawera Home Guard in early 1942.<ref>{{cite news|title=Personal Items|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/CHP19420124.2.40|accessdate=3 February 2018|work=Press|issue=23545|date=24 January 1942}}</ref> Late the following year he was appointed commander of the Hawera squadron of the Air Training Corps<ref>{{cite news|title=Army Appointments|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19431217.2.30|accessdate=1 April 2018|work=Auckland Star|agency=Press Association|issue=Vol. LXXIV, issue 299|date=17 December 1943}}</ref> and held this post until 1945. He was formally seconded to the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] for a brief period as a squadron commander of 34th Air Training Squadron before ceasing active duty at the end of the war. He formally retired from the military in 1949.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}\n\nAt the age of 61, Laurent went to London in 1956 as part of the VC [[centenary]] celebrations. He attended further VC events in the following years.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} He died in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]] on 9 December 1987, the last surviving New Zealand VC winner of the First World War.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} His wife had predeceased him the previous year.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} His ashes are interred in the Memorial Wall at the Servicemen's Cemetery at Hawera, his hometown.{{sfn|Harper|Richardson|2007|pp=171\u2013172}} A street in the town is also named after him, and nearby is Grant VC Street, named for fellow VC recipient John Grant.<ref name=Kete>{{cite web|title=Grant VC Street|url=http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/taranaki_street_names/topics/show/2545-grant-vc-street-tdn-23012016|website=Kete New Plymouth|accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nLaurent's VC was displayed at the [[QEII Army Memorial Museum]] in [[Waiouru, New Zealand|Waiouru]], along with his service medals from the First and Second World Wars and his coronation medals.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=238\u2013239}} On 2 December 2007, Laurent's VC was one of nine Victoria Crosses that were among a hundred medals stolen from the museum. On 16 February 2008, New Zealand Police announced all the medals had been recovered as a result of a [[New Zealand dollar|NZ$]]300,000 reward offered by [[Michael Ashcroft, Baron Ashcroft|Michael Ashcroft]] and Tom Sturgess.<ref>{{cite web|author=NZPA|title=Medals stolen from Waiouru Army Museum recovered |publisher=nzherald|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10492853|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120907072955/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10492853|archivedate=7 September 2012|date=16 February 2008|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{portal|Biography|World War I}}\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Austin|first=Lieut.-Col W. S.|title=The Official History of the New Zealand Rifle Brigade|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-WH1-NZRi.html|year=1924|publisher=L. T. Watkins Limited|location=Wellington, New Zealand|oclc=220312361|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=Road to Victory 1918|series=[[VCs of the First World War]]|year=2014|origyear=2004|publisher=History Press|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire, United Kingdom|isbn=978-0-7509-5361-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Harper|first=Glyn|authorlink=Glyn Harper|last2=Richardson|first2=Colin|title=In the Face of the Enemy: The Complete History of the Victoria Cross and New Zealand|year=2007|publisher=HarperCollins|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=978-1-86950-650-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=McGibbon|editor-first=Ian|editorlink=Ian McGibbon|author-last=McGibbon|author-first=Ian|chapter=New Zealand Expeditionary Force|pages=364\u2013369|title=The Oxford Companion to New Zealand Military History|year=2000a|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=0-19-558376-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=McGibbon|editor-first=Ian|editorlink=Ian McGibbon|author-last=McGibbon|author-first=Ian|chapter=Laurent, Lieutenant-Colonel Harry John|page=274|title=The Oxford Companion to New Zealand Military History|year=2000b|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=0-19-558376-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=McGibbon|editor-first=Ian|editorlink=Ian McGibbon|author-last=O'Shea|author-first=Phillip|chapter=Victoria Cross|pages=558\u2013561|title=The Oxford Companion to New Zealand Military History|year=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=0-19-558376-0|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laurent, Harry John}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Army personnel]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Rifle Brigade (Earl of Liverpool's Own)]]\n[[Category:New Zealand World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n", "name_user": "Onco p53", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: Hawera \u2192 H\u0101wera (15)  as perWikipedia:Naming_conventions_(New_Zealand)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Laurent"}
{"title_page": "Karen Clark Sheard", "text_new": "{{peacock|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Karen Clark Sheard\n| Picture          = karen-clark-sheard-1.jpg\n| caption          = Clark\u2013Sheard, 2010. \n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            =  Karen Clark Sheard-photo-by-raymond-boyd.jpg\n| birth_name       = Karen Valencia Clark\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1960|11|15}}<ref>[https://twitter.com/officialkcs/status/4716036284743681 Clark-Sheard's Twitter]</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Detroit, Michigan]], U.S.\n| origin           = Detroit, Michigan\n| instrument       = {{hlist|[[Singing|Vocals]]|[[Musical Keyboard|keyboards]]|[[Organ (music)|organ]]|[[Drum kit|drums]]}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Gospel music|Gospel]]|[[urban contemporary gospel|Urban gospel]]|[[Contemporary Christian music|CCM]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|[[Singing|Singer]]|[[songwriter]]|[[musician]]|[[actress]]}}\n| years_active     = 1966\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Island Records|Island Black Music]]|[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]|[[Word Records|Word]]|Karew}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[The Clark Sisters]]|[[Kierra \"Kiki\" Sheard]]|[[Twinkie Clark|Elbernita \"Twinkie\" Clark]]|[[Dorinda Clark Cole]]|[[Jacky Clark Chisholm]]|[[Mattie Moss Clark]]|[[J. Moss]]}}\n| website          = {{url|theclarksisters.net}}<br>{{url|KarewRecords.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Karen Valencia Clark\u2013Sheard''' (born November 15, 1960) is an American Grammy Award-winning [[gospel music|gospel]] singer, musician, and songwriter. Clark\u2013Sheard is best known as the youngest member of the American gospel group [[The Clark Sisters]]. Clark\u2013Sheard is the mother of [[Urban contemporary gospel|contemporary gospel]] singer and actress [[Kierra Sheard|Kierra \"Kiki\" Sheard]]. She has released five solo albums, seventeen with The Clark Sisters and collaborated with her son J. Drew Sheard her daughter Kierra Sheard.\n\nDuring the hiatus of the Clark Sisters, Clark\u2013Sheard rose to fame after she recorded her critically acclaimed and much anticipated solo album ''[[Finally Karen (album)|Finally Karen]]'', which spawned her hit, \"Balm in Gilead\" (a re-recording of a song she originally recorded as part of The Clark Sisters back in the 1980s for their ''Heart & Soul'' album) the R&B-flavored \"Just For Me\" and \"Nothing Without You\" \u2013 a contemporary duet with R&B diva [[Faith Evans]]. ''[[Finally Karen]]'' became one of the most successful gospel albums of 1998 earning Sheard a Grammy nomination and earning her a Soul Train Lady of Soul Award for \"Best Female Vocalist\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theclarksisters.com/karen.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070519004558/http://www.theclarksisters.com/karen.html |archivedate=2007-05-19 }}</ref>\n\nAfter her debut album success and much touring, Clark\u2013Sheard was hospitalized in 2001 after one of her blood vessels burst during a minor surgery, resulting in doctors giving her a 2% chance of survival. Her testimony inspired the title name for her long-awaited sophomore project, ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]'' released in 2002, featuring \"A Secret Place\" \u2013 which is now considered a classic amongst fans. Clark\u2013Sheard recorded two more live albums, including ''[[The Heavens Are Telling (album)|The Heavens Are Telling]]'' and ''[[It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)|It's Not Over]]'' (which featured some studio recordings), before releasing ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]'', Clark\u2013Sheard's first all-studio-recorded album in 13 years. The album debuted at #3 on the [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Chart]] and #98 on ''Billboard'''s [[Billboard 200|Top 200 albums]] chart, while its first single \"Prayed Up\" has so far peaked at #10 on the U.S. [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' Gospel Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=karen clark-sheard|chart=all}}|title=Crazy Praise \u2013 Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSingers [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Mariah Carey]], [[Faith Evans]], [[Coko]] of [[SWV]], Jovan Lacroix, [[Blu Cantrell]], [[Lil' Mo]], [[Missy Elliott]], and [[Fantasia (singer)|Fantasia]] all count Clark-Sheard as one of their vocal influences.<ref name=\"gfinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gospelflava.com/articles/karenclarksheardinterview2006.html|title=An interview with Karen Clark Sheard|author=Jones, Steven|publisher=GospelFlava.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/artists/karenclarksheard.html|title=Karen Clark Sheard Biography}}</ref>\n==Biography==\n===Early life and education===\nClark\u2013Sheard was born '''Karen Valencia Clark''' on November 15, 1960 in [[Detroit, Michigan]], the youngest child of Reverend Elbert Clark and [[Mattie Moss Clark|Dr. Mattie Moss Clark]], a pioneering gospel choral director. The youngest of six children, Clark\u2013Sheard's siblings are Leo, [[Jacky Clark Chisholm|Jacky]], Denise, [[Twinkie Clark|Elbernita \"Twinkie\"]] and [[Dorinda Clark Cole|Dorinda]]. Clark\u2013Sheard began singing gospel with her sisters at age 6 in what became known as [[The Clark Sisters]]. For high school, Clark-Sheard attended [[Mumford High School]] in Detroit, Michigan; graduating in 1979.\n\n===Career===\n====The Clark Sisters====\n{{Main|The Clark Sisters}}\n====Debut album====\n{{Main|Finally Karen}}\nClark\u2013Sheard's involvement in the Island Inspirational All Stars' \"[[Don't Give Up (Kirk Franklin song)|Don't Give Up]]\" in 1996 (along with [[Donald Lawrence]], [[Hezekiah Walker]], and [[Kirk Franklin]]) led to her signing with Island Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/artists/36|title=Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=GospelCity.com|date=March 22, 2000|access-date=December 12, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427091826/http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/artists/36|archive-date=April 27, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> Clark\u2013Sheard's solo career began with the release of her debut album ''[[Finally Karen]]'' in [[1997 in music|1997]]. The album, consisting of half studio recordings and half live recordings, was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album in 1998, won Clark-Sheard the Lady of Soul award for Best Gospel Album that same year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/factsheets/awardsdb/env-awards-db-search,0,7169155.htmlstory?searchtype=person&query=finally+karen|title=Award Nominations at The Envelope|publisher=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> and peaked at #28 and #2 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums]] charts respectively.\n====A Second Chance====\n{{Main|2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)}}\nAfter [[Yolanda Adams]], Clark-Sheard became the 2nd gospel artist to sign to [[Elektra Records]]. She released her Elektra debut album ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]'' in 2002 (so named because of the \"second chance\" she was given by [[God]] after her near-death experience \u2013 which is referenced in her daughter Kierra's song \"[[You Don't Know (Kierra Sheard song)|You Don't Know]]\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurweb.com/story/eur7588.cfm|title=Karen Clark Sheard Gets '2nd Chance'|publisher=EURweb.com|author1=McIntyre, Donald  |author2=Kiel, Danna|date=August 1, 2002}}</ref> The album was led off by the single \"Be Sure\" and though Clark\u2013Sheard was in excellent form vocally, the slick, progressive sound of the disc was not received well in the gospel community.  However, the album still performed well commercially and critically reaching #82 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200, #27 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums chart (her highest chartings on those charts to date) and #2 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums.\n====The Heavens Are Telling====\n{{Main|The Heavens Are Telling}}\nThe 2003 followup ''[[The Heavens Are Telling (album)|The Heavens Are Telling]]'' fared well, but came at an awkward time when Elektra Records was being dissolved into [[Atlantic Records]] and so failed to match the commercial success of Clark-Sheard's previous albums, peaking a whole 106 places below ''2nd Chance'' at #188 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 \u2013 though it managed to reach a respectable #44 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums, a high #3 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums chart and was her first album to chart on the [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Christian Albums]] chart, where it peaked at #11.<ref name=\"BillboardChart\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=karen clark-sheard|chart=all}}|title=The Heavens Are Telling \u2013 Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=Billboard.com}}</ref>\n====It's Not Over====\n{{Main|It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)}}\nIn 2005, after a bidding war with several labels, Clark-Sheard finally signed with Word Records and issued ''[[It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)|It's Not Over]]'', (Originally titled ''Finally Karen Returns''), the sequel to her 1997 debut album ''[[Finally Karen]]'' was set to be released November 15, 2005, Clark-Sheard's 45th birthday, but was delayed and released the following year. Most of ''It's Not Over'' was recorded live in 2005 at Karen's home church in Detroit, Michigan while the last three tracks were studio-recorded. \n\nIt was Clark-Sheard's first solo album not to feature guest vocals from her daughter (Kierra Sheard) and was the first to include production from [[Israel Houghton]] \u2013 who handled the majority of the project. Despite having a much grander sound than her previous albums, it was another critical success for Karen and charted modestly at #124 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 and #4 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums.<ref name=\"BillboardChart\"/><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=karen clark-sheard|chart=all}}|title=It's Not Over \u2013 Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=Billboard.com}}</ref> As the songwriter, on February 10, 2008, Clark-Sheard won the [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Song]] for \"Blessed & Highly Favored\" sung by [[The Clark Sisters]].\n====Karew Records, 5th album and present====\n{{Main|All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)}}\nIn early 2009, Clark-Sheard and her husband, J.Drew Sheard partnered together and launched a new record label entitled [[Karew Records]] (Karew being a combination of both their forenames: Karen & Drew, pronounced: Kuh-rue); Distribution is via EMI Gospel. The Clark Sisters' Christmas album \u2013 which was released in October 2009 \u2013 was the first project to be released from Karew Records.\n\nOn January 31, 2010, Clark-Sheard won the [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Performance]] for ''Wait on the Lord'' which she was featured with [[Donnie McClurkin]]. On April 6, 2010, Clark-Sheard released her fifth album (and first on her newly founded own record label \u2013 Karew Records) titled ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]'', which features additional vocals from her daughter Kierra Sheard, son J. Drew Sheard II, sister [[Dorinda Clark Cole]], niece Angel Chisholm and cousin [[J. Moss]]. Though her first all-studio-recorded album since her 2002 release ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]'', ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]'' managed to debut and peak at #98 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 (her second highest charting on that chart to date) and #3 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums chart, while the album's lead single \u2013 \"Prayed Up\" \u2013 peaked at #9 and stayed over 22 weeks on the [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Gospel Songs]] chart. Clark-Sheard released her latest single \"[[Sunday A.M]]\" in 2014, which is nominated for the [[Best Gospel Song]] in the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].\n\nAs of 2019, Clark-Sheard is in talks to play Kitty Parham, a member of The Famous Ward Singers in [[Aretha Franklin]]'s upcoming biopic ''[[Respect (2020 film)|Respect]]''.<ref>http://praiseindy.com/national/donnas/karen-clark-sheard-in-talks-to-play-aretha-franklin/</ref>\n\nKaren was portrayed by her daughter, [[Kierra Sheard]] in the [[Lifetime TV]] biopic The Clark Sisters: First Ladies of Gospel, released April 11, 2020.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10098482/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriage and family===\nClark-Sheard has been married once and has two children. On June 16, 1984, Clark-Sheard married Bishop J. Drew Sheard, a Detroit-based minister. Her husband is senior pastor of Greater Emmanuel Institutional [[Church of God in Christ]] in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]]. Together they have two children: [[Kierra Sheard|Kierra]] \"Kiki\" Sheard (1987) and John Drew \"J. Drew\" Sheard II (1989). Kiki is also a gospel recording artist, with four albums, plus various projects to her credit. J. Drew is a musician and producer. He has a son named Jacob Dillon Sheard and daughter named Kali Drew Sheard.\n===Health===\nIn 2001, Clark-Sheard was faced with a life-threatening crisis when a [[blood vessel]] burst during a scheduled bariatric surgery. Her doctors only gave her a 2% chance of survival due to her complications. After the [[blood clot]] was surgically removed, Clark-Sheard fell into a [[coma]]. The coma lasted three and a half weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/interviews/2006/karenclarksheard-0206.html|title=Back From The Dead|publisher=Christianity Today|date=February 20, 2006|author=Taylor, LaTonya}}</ref> but Clark-Sheard says she made a miraculous<ref>[http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/interviews/54 Gospel City Interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050307004731/http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/interviews/54 |date=2005-03-07 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.christianmusicplanet.com/magazine/viewarticle.asp?id=525 Christian Music Planet]</ref> recovery.\n\n==Tours and concerts==\n*(1989) The Clark Sisters: Bringing It Back Home\n*(1997) Finally Karen\n*(2007-2008) The Clark Sisters: Live One Last Time Tour\n*(2016-2017) Festival Of Praise\n*(2016-2017) McDonald's Celebration of Gospel\n==Filmography==\n*2009 \" [[Stellar Awards]]\" ([[Donnie McClurkin]])\n*2010 ''Blessed & Cursed'' (movie)\n*2010 \"[[BET Awards]]\"(All Star)\n*2010 \" [[Trumpet Awards]]\" ([[The Clark Sisters]])\n*2011 \"[[Stellar Awards]]\" ( [[Kirk Franklin]] tribute)\n*2011\u20132012 ''[[Church Girl]]'' (stage play)\n*2012 ''[[For Richer or Poorer (play)|For Richer or Poorer]]''' (stage play)\n*2012 \"[[BMI Urban Music Awards]]\" ([[Mariah Carey]] tribute)\n*2013 \"[[The Sheards]]\"\n*2013 \"[[BET Celebration of Gospel]]\"\n*2014 \"[[The BET Honors]]\"\n*2017 \"Xscape: Still Kickin It\" ([[Xscape (group)|Xscape]] Rocks the Stage, Episode 4)\n*2020 \u201cThe Clark Sisters: First Ladies of Gospel\"\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Karen Clark Sheard discography}}\n\n===Compilations===\n*2011: ''[[The Ultimate Collection (Karen Clark Sheard album)|The Ultimate Collection]] \u2013 compilation\n\n===Studio albums===\n*Nov. 1997: ''[[Finally Karen (album)|Finally Karen]]''\n*Jan. 2002: ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]''\n*Nov. 2003: ''[[The Heavens Are Telling (album)|The Heavens Are Telling]]''\n*Jan. 2006: ''[[It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)|It's Not Over]]''\n*Apr. 2010: ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]''\n\n===Live albums===\n*Jul. 2015: ''[[Destined to Win (Karen Clark Sheard album)|Destined to Win]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.theclarksisters.net/ Official website of The Clark Sisters]\n{{The Clark Sisters}}\n{{Moss-Clark-Sheard}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheard, Karen Clark}}\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Singers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Detroit]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Church of God in Christ]]\n[[Category:American Pentecostals]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{peacock|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Karen Clark Sheard\n| Picture          = karen-clark-sheard-1.jpg\n| caption          = Clark\u2013Sheard, 2010. \n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            =  Karen Clark Sheard-photo-by-raymond-boyd.jpg\n| birth_name       = Karen Valencia Clark\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1960|11|15}}<ref>[https://twitter.com/officialkcs/status/4716036284743681 Clark-Sheard's Twitter]</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Detroit, Michigan]], U.S.\n| origin           = Detroit, Michigan\n| instrument       = {{hlist|[[Singing|Vocals]]|[[Musical Keyboard|keyboards]]|[[Organ (music)|organ]]|[[Drum kit|drums]]}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Gospel music|Gospel]]|[[urban contemporary gospel|Urban gospel]]|[[Contemporary Christian music|CCM]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|[[Singing|Singer]]|[[songwriter]]|[[musician]]|[[actress]]}}\n| years_active     = 1966\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Island Records|Island Black Music]]|[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]|[[Word Records|Word]]|Karew}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[The Clark Sisters]]|[[Kierra \"Kiki\" Sheard]]|[[Twinkie Clark|Elbernita \"Twinkie\" Clark]]|[[Dorinda Clark Cole]]|[[Jacky Clark Chisholm]]|[[Mattie Moss Clark]]|[[J. Moss]]}}\n| website          = {{url|theclarksisters.net}}<br>{{url|KarewRecords.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Karen Valencia Clark\u2013Sheard''' (born November 15, 1960) is an American Grammy Award-winning [[gospel music|gospel]] singer, musician, and songwriter. Clark\u2013Sheard is best known as the youngest member of the American gospel group [[The Clark Sisters]]. Clark\u2013Sheard is the mother of [[Urban contemporary gospel|contemporary gospel]] singer and actress [[Kierra Sheard|Kierra \"Kiki\" Sheard]]. She has released five solo albums, seventeen with The Clark Sisters and collaborated with her son J. Drew Sheard her daughter Kierra Sheard.\n\nDuring the hiatus of the Clark Sisters, Clark\u2013Sheard rose to fame after she recorded her critically acclaimed and much anticipated solo album ''[[Finally Karen (album)|Finally Karen]]'', which spawned her hit, \"Balm in Gilead\" (a re-recording of a song she originally recorded as part of The Clark Sisters back in the 1980s for their ''Heart & Soul'' album) the R&B-flavored \"Just For Me\" and \"Nothing Without You\" \u2013 a contemporary duet with R&B diva [[Faith Evans]]. ''[[Finally Karen]]'' became one of the most successful gospel albums of 1998 earning Sheard a Grammy nomination and earning her a Soul Train Lady of Soul Award for \"Best Female Vocalist\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theclarksisters.com/karen.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070519004558/http://www.theclarksisters.com/karen.html |archivedate=2007-05-19 }}</ref>\n\nAfter her debut album success and much touring, Clark\u2013Sheard was hospitalized in 2001 after one of her blood vessels burst during a minor surgery, resulting in doctors giving her a 2% chance of survival. Her testimony inspired the title name for her long-awaited sophomore project, ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]'' released in 2002, featuring \"A Secret Place\" \u2013 which is now considered a classic amongst fans. Clark\u2013Sheard recorded two more live albums, including ''[[The Heavens Are Telling (album)|The Heavens Are Telling]]'' and ''[[It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)|It's Not Over]]'' (which featured some studio recordings), before releasing ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]'', Clark\u2013Sheard's first all-studio-recorded album in 13 years. The album debuted at #3 on the [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Chart]] and #98 on ''Billboard'''s [[Billboard 200|Top 200 albums]] chart, while its first single \"Prayed Up\" has so far peaked at #10 on the U.S. [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' Gospel Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=karen clark-sheard|chart=all}}|title=Crazy Praise \u2013 Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSingers [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Mariah Carey]], [[Faith Evans]], [[Coko]] of [[SWV]], Jovan Lacroix, [[Blu Cantrell]], [[Lil' Mo]], [[Missy Elliott]], and [[Fantasia (singer)|Fantasia]] all count Clark-Sheard as one of their vocal influences.<ref name=\"gfinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gospelflava.com/articles/karenclarksheardinterview2006.html|title=An interview with Karen Clark Sheard|author=Jones, Steven|publisher=GospelFlava.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/artists/karenclarksheard.html|title=Karen Clark Sheard Biography}}</ref>\n==Biography==\n===Early life and education===\nClark\u2013Sheard was born '''Karen Valencia Clark''' on November 15, 1960 in [[Detroit, Michigan]], the youngest child of Reverend Elbert Clark and [[Mattie Moss Clark|Dr. Mattie Moss Clark]], a pioneering gospel choral director. The youngest of six children, Clark\u2013Sheard's siblings are Leo, [[Jacky Clark Chisholm|Jacky]], Denise, [[Twinkie Clark|Elbernita \"Twinkie\"]] and [[Dorinda Clark Cole|Dorinda]]. Clark\u2013Sheard began singing gospel with her sisters at age 6 in what became known as [[The Clark Sisters]]. For high school, Clark-Sheard attended [[Mumford High School]] in Detroit, Michigan; graduating in 1979.\n\n===Career===\n====The Clark Sisters====\n{{Main|The Clark Sisters}}\n====Debut album====\n{{Main|Finally Karen}}\nClark\u2013Sheard's involvement in the Island Inspirational All Stars' \"[[Don't Give Up (Kirk Franklin song)|Don't Give Up]]\" in 1996 (along with [[Donald Lawrence]], [[Hezekiah Walker]], and [[Kirk Franklin]]) led to her signing with Island Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/artists/36|title=Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=GospelCity.com|date=March 22, 2000|access-date=December 12, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427091826/http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/artists/36|archive-date=April 27, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> Clark\u2013Sheard's solo career began with the release of her debut album ''[[Finally Karen]]'' in [[1997 in music|1997]]. The album, consisting of half studio recordings and half live recordings, was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album in 1998, won Clark-Sheard the Lady of Soul award for Best Gospel Album that same year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/factsheets/awardsdb/env-awards-db-search,0,7169155.htmlstory?searchtype=person&query=finally+karen|title=Award Nominations at The Envelope|publisher=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> and peaked at #28 and #2 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums]] charts respectively.\n====A Second Chance====\n{{Main|2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)}}\nAfter [[Yolanda Adams]], Clark-Sheard became the 2nd gospel artist to sign to [[Elektra Records]]. She released her Elektra debut album ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]'' in 2002 (so named because of the \"second chance\" she was given by [[God]] after her near-death experience \u2013 which is referenced in her daughter Kierra's song \"[[You Don't Know (Kierra Sheard song)|You Don't Know]]\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurweb.com/story/eur7588.cfm|title=Karen Clark Sheard Gets '2nd Chance'|publisher=EURweb.com|author1=McIntyre, Donald  |author2=Kiel, Danna|date=August 1, 2002}}</ref> The album was led off by the single \"Be Sure\" and though Clark\u2013Sheard was in excellent form vocally, the slick, progressive sound of the disc was not received well in the gospel community.  However, the album still performed well commercially and critically reaching #82 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200, #27 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums chart (her highest chartings on those charts to date) and #2 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums.\n====The Heavens Are Telling====\n{{Main|The Heavens Are Telling}}\nThe 2003 followup ''[[The Heavens Are Telling (album)|The Heavens Are Telling]]'' fared well, but came at an awkward time when Elektra Records was being dissolved into [[Atlantic Records]] and so failed to match the commercial success of Clark-Sheard's previous albums, peaking a whole 106 places below ''2nd Chance'' at #188 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 \u2013 though it managed to reach a respectable #44 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums, a high #3 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums chart and was her first album to chart on the [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Christian Albums]] chart, where it peaked at #11.<ref name=\"BillboardChart\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=karen clark-sheard|chart=all}}|title=The Heavens Are Telling \u2013 Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=Billboard.com}}</ref>\n====It's Not Over====\n{{Main|It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)}}\nIn 2005, after a bidding war with several labels, Clark-Sheard finally signed with Word Records and issued ''[[It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)|It's Not Over]]'', (Originally titled ''Finally Karen Returns''), the sequel to her 1997 debut album ''[[Finally Karen]]'' was set to be released November 15, 2005, Clark-Sheard's 45th birthday, but was delayed and released the following year. Most of ''It's Not Over'' was recorded live in 2005 at Karen's home church in Detroit, Michigan while the last three tracks were studio-recorded. \n\nIt was Clark-Sheard's first solo album not to feature guest vocals from her daughter (Kierra Sheard) and was the first to include production from [[Israel Houghton]] \u2013 who handled the majority of the project. Despite having a much grander sound than her previous albums, it was another critical success for Karen and charted modestly at #124 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 and #4 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums.<ref name=\"BillboardChart\"/><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=karen clark-sheard|chart=all}}|title=It's Not Over \u2013 Karen Clark Sheard|publisher=Billboard.com}}</ref> As the songwriter, on February 10, 2008, Clark-Sheard won the [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Song]] for \"Blessed & Highly Favored\" sung by [[The Clark Sisters]].\n====Karew Records, 5th album and present====\n{{Main|All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)}}\nIn early 2009, Clark-Sheard and her husband, J.Drew Sheard partnered together and launched a new record label entitled [[Karew Records]] (Karew being a combination of both their forenames: Karen & Drew, pronounced: Kuh-rue); Distribution is via EMI Gospel. The Clark Sisters' Christmas album \u2013 which was released in October 2009 \u2013 was the first project to be released from Karew Records.\n\nOn January 31, 2010, Clark-Sheard won the [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Performance]] for ''Wait on the Lord'' which she was featured with [[Donnie McClurkin]]. On April 6, 2010, Clark-Sheard released her fifth album (and first on her newly founded own record label \u2013 Karew Records) titled ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]'', which features additional vocals from her daughter Kierra Sheard, son J. Drew Sheard II, sister [[Dorinda Clark Cole]], niece Angel Chisholm and cousin [[J. Moss]]. Though her first all-studio-recorded album since her 2002 release ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]'', ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]'' managed to debut and peak at #98 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 (her second highest charting on that chart to date) and #3 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Gospel Albums chart, while the album's lead single \u2013 \"Prayed Up\" \u2013 peaked at #9 and stayed over 22 weeks on the [[Billboard charts|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Gospel Songs]] chart. Clark-Sheard released her latest single \"[[Sunday A.M]]\" in 2014, which is nominated for the [[Best Gospel Song]] in the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].\n\nAs of 2019, Clark-Sheard is in talks to play Kitty Parham, a member of The Famous Ward Singers in [[Aretha Franklin]]'s upcoming biopic ''[[Respect (2020 film)|Respect]]''.<ref>http://praiseindy.com/national/donnas/karen-clark-sheard-in-talks-to-play-aretha-franklin/</ref>\n\nKaren was portrayed by her daughter, [[Kierra Sheard]] in the [[Lifetime TV]] biopic The Clark Sisters: First Ladies of Gospel, released April 11, 2020.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10098482/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriage and family===\nClark-Sheard has been married once and has two children. On June 16, 1984, Clark-Sheard married Bishop J. Drew Sheard, a Detroit-based minister. Her husband is senior pastor of Greater Emmanuel Institutional [[Church of God in Christ]] in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]]. Together they have two children: [[Kierra Sheard|Kierra]] \"Kiki\" Sheard (1987) and John Drew \"J. Drew\" Sheard II (1989). Kiki is also a gospel recording artist, with four albums, plus various projects to her credit. J. Drew is a musician and producer. He has a son named Jacob Dillon Sheard and daughter named Kali Drew Sheard.\n===Health===\nIn 2001, Clark-Sheard was faced with a life-threatening crisis when a [[blood vessel]] burst during a scheduled bariatric surgery. Her doctors only gave her a 2% chance of survival due to her complications. After the [[blood clot]] was surgically removed, Clark-Sheard fell into a [[coma]]. The coma lasted three and a half weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/interviews/2006/karenclarksheard-0206.html|title=Back From The Dead|publisher=Christianity Today|date=February 20, 2006|author=Taylor, LaTonya}}</ref> but Clark-Sheard says she made a miraculous<ref>[http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/interviews/54 Gospel City Interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050307004731/http://www.gospelcity.com/dynamic/artist-articles/interviews/54 |date=2005-03-07 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.christianmusicplanet.com/magazine/viewarticle.asp?id=525 Christian Music Planet]</ref> recovery.\n\n==Tours and concerts==\n*(1989) The Clark Sisters: Bringing It Back Home\n*(1997) Finally Karen\n*(2007-2008) The Clark Sisters: Live One Last Time Tour\n*(2016-2017) Festival Of Praise\n*(2016-2017) McDonald's Celebration of Gospel\n==Filmography==\n*2009 \" [[Stellar Awards]]\" ([[Donnie McClurkin]])\n*2010 ''Blessed & Cursed'' (movie)\n*2010 \"[[BET Awards]]\"(All Star)\n*2010 \" [[Trumpet Awards]]\" ([[The Clark Sisters]])\n*2011 \"[[Stellar Awards]]\" ( [[Kirk Franklin]] tribute)\n*2011\u20132012 ''[[Church Girl]]'' (stage play)\n*2012 ''[[For Richer or Poorer (play)|For Richer or Poorer]]''' (stage play)\n*2012 \"[[BMI Urban Music Awards]]\" ([[Mariah Carey]] tribute)\n*2013 \"[[The Sheards]]\"\n*2013 \"[[BET Celebration of Gospel]]\"\n*2014 \"[[The BET Honors]]\"\n*2017 \"Xscape: Still Kickin It\" ([[Xscape (group)|Xscape]] Rocks the Stage, Episode 4)\n*2020 \u201cThe Clark Sisters: First Ladies of Gospel\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Karen Clark Sheard discography}}\n\n===Compilations===\n*2011: ''[[The Ultimate Collection (Karen Clark Sheard album)|The Ultimate Collection]] \u2013 compilation\n\n===Studio albums===\n*Nov. 1997: ''[[Finally Karen (album)|Finally Karen]]''\n*Jan. 2002: ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]''\n*Nov. 2003: ''[[The Heavens Are Telling (album)|The Heavens Are Telling]]''\n*Jan. 2006: ''[[It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)|It's Not Over]]''\n*Apr. 2010: ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]]''\n\n===Live albums===\n*Jul. 2015: ''[[Destined to Win (Karen Clark Sheard album)|Destined to Win]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.theclarksisters.net/ Official website of The Clark Sisters]\n{{The Clark Sisters}}\n{{Moss-Clark-Sheard}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheard, Karen Clark}}\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Singers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Detroit]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Church of God in Christ]]\n[[Category:American Pentecostals]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Atlphotos89", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karen_Clark_Sheard"}
