{"title_page": "Where Are You Christmas?", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Where Are You Christmas?\n| cover      = Faith Hill - Where Are You Christmas?.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Faith Hill]]\n| album      = [[Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000 film)#Soundtrack|How the Grinch Stole Christmas ''soundtrack'']]\n| released   = {{date|2000-12-11|MDY}}\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   = 2000\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Christmas music|Christmas]]|[[Country music|country]]|[[Pop music|pop]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=4|s=07}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros. Nashville]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Mariah Carey]]|[[James Horner]]|[[Will Jennings]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Byron Gallimore]]|Faith Hill}}\n| prev_title = [[Let's Make Love (song)|Let's Make Love]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[If My Heart Had Wings]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\n\"'''Christmas, Why Can't I Find You?'''\" is a song written by Mariah Carey, [[James Horner]] and [[Will Jennings]] for the movie ''[[Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000 film)|How the Grinch Stole Christmas]]'' in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0170016/soundtrack|title=How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000) - Soundtracks|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2013-08-10}}</ref> In the film, it is first sung by [[Taylor Momsen]], who played [[Cindy Lou Who]].<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://est1997.com/music/where-are-you-christmas-mariah-careys-unsung-holiday-classic/|title=Where Are You Christmas? Mariah Carey's Unsung Holiday Classic|date=2017-12-17|publisher=Established in 1997|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref> \n\n[[Mariah Carey]] wrote a full-length version of the song with additional lyrics, renamed \"'''Where Are You Christmas?'''\", for the film's soundtrack. The song was originally recorded by Carey, but because of a [[legal case]] with her ex-husband [[Tommy Mottola]], it could not be released, so it was re-recorded and released by [[Faith Hill]].<ref name=history /> A [[CD single]] of Hill's rendition was released December 11, 2000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where Are You Christmas ? |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Where-Are-Christmas-Faith-Hill/dp/B000056WGS |website=[[Amazon UK]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> A video was released featuring Hill singing from the [[Grinch]]'s mountaintop home, interspersed with clips from the film and a cameo appearance by Momsen as Cindy Lou Who.\n\n==Composition==\n\"Where Are You Christmas?\" is a [[power ballad]] written by James Horner and Will Jennings, with additional lyrics provided by Mariah Carey.<ref name=history/> The song is composed in the key of [[B-flat major|B{{flat}} major]] and set to a slow tempo of 56 [[tempo#Beats per minute|BPM]].<ref name=\"sheet music\">{{cite web |title=Faith Hill \"Where Are You Christmas?\" Sheet Music in B{{flat}} Major |url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0038180 |publisher=[[Universal Music Publishing Group]] via Musicnotes.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> Hill's vocals range almost two octaves, from F{{sub|3}} to E{{flat}}{{sub|5}}.<ref name=\"sheet music\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nBilly Dukes of ''[[Taste of Country]]'' ranked \"Where Are You Christmas?\" at number 6 on a list of the top 50 [[country music|country]] [[Christmas song]]s, writing that the song was \"touching\" and that \"Hill performs it like a woman at the top of her game, which she certainly was.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dukes |first1=Billy |title=No. 6: Faith Hill, 'Where Are You Christmas' - Top 50 Country Christmas Songs |url=https://tasteofcountry.com/faith-hill-where-are-you-christmas-top-50-country-christmas-songs/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=[[Taste of Country]] |date=November 19, 2012}}</ref> Describing the song as underrated, Pip Ellwood-Hughes of ''Entertainment Focus'' praised Hill's vocal performance, writing that \"[she] sounds incredible as she unleashes the full range of her powerful voice.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ellwood-Hughes |first1=Pip |title=EF Country Advent Calendar Day 5: Faith Hill \u2013 Where Are You Christmas? |url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/ef-country/ef-country-advent-calendar-day-5-faith-hill-where-are-you-christmas/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=Entertainment Focus |date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nConversely, ''[[The Atlantic]]'' labeled the song as one of the top ten \"most annoying\" holiday songs. \"She sounds like a crazy person asking after an imaginary friend,\" writes Cameron Martin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Cameron |title=The 10 Most Annoying and Ubiquitous Holiday Songs |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2010/12/the-10-most-annoying-and-ubiquitous-holiday-songs/67585/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=December 7, 2010}}</ref> Steve Simels of ''[[TV Guide]]'' was critical of \"Where Are You Christmas?\" in his review of the Grinch film, writing that \"none but the thoroughly perverse of hearing should stick around for the closing credits and Faith Hill warbling\" the song.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Simels |first1=Steve |title=Dr. Seuss' How The Grinch Stole Christmas - Movie Reviews and Movie Ratings |url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/dr-seuss-how-the-grinch-stole-christmas/review/134709/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Where Are You Christmas?\" peaked at number 10 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart in January 2001, becoming Hill's fifth top ten single at that format.<ref name=\"adult contemporary\"/> The song experienced [[crossover music|crossover]] success at radio, peaking at number 26 on the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart and at number 40 on the [[Adult Pop Songs]] chart, in addition to reaching a peak position of 65 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In 2013, \"Where Are You Christmas?\" peaked at number 15 on the seasonal Holiday 100 chart,<ref name=\"holiday 100\"/> on which it has continued making appearances throughout the 2010s.<ref name=history/> The song has never entered the [[Canadian Hot 100]], but did reach a peak position of 38 of the [[Hot Canadian Digital Songs]] component chart in 2018.<ref name=\"Canada digital\"/>\n\n\"Where Are You Christmas\" was placed seventh{{efn|At the time of the article's publication in November 2016, the song ranked at number seven with a sales figure of 897,000. With certified sales of 977,000 as of December 2018, the song should now ostensibly rank at number six ahead of \"[[Christmas Canon]]\".}} on the list of all-time [[Best-selling Christmas/holiday singles in the United States|best-selling Christmas/holiday digital singles]] in SoundScan history in  2016.<ref>{{cite web|author= Billboard Staff|date= November 25, 2016 |title= What Are the Top-Selling Holiday Songs? |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7588783/what-are-the-top-selling-christmas-music-holiday-songs |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate= December 2, 2016}}</ref> \nAs of December 2019, total digital sales of the Faith Hill recording has reached 1,002,000 downloads according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |title=Top 30 Digital Country Tracks - Pure Sales: December 9, 2019 |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2019/12/44071-top-30-digital-country-tracks-pure-sales-december-9-2019 |work=Rough Stock |date=December 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (2000-18)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada [[Hot Canadian Digital Songs|Hot Digital Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"canada digital\">{{cite web |title=Faith Hill Chart History (Hot Canadian Digital Song Sales) |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Faith-Hill/chart-history/CNS |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| 38\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch40|37|artist=Faith Hill|song=Where Are You Christmas?|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|35|artist=Faith Hill|song=Where Are You Christmas?|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|65|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardadultcontemporary|10|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019|refname=\"adult contemporary\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardadultpopsongs|40|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Holiday 100 (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"holiday 100\">{{cite web |title=Faith Hill Chart History (Holiday 100) |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Faith-Hill/chart-history/HSX |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| 15\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|26|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|}\n\n==Other versions==\n\"Where Are You Christmas?\" has been [[cover version|covered]] by a variety of artists since its release, including Ali & Theo, [[The Blenders]], Charlie Miller, The Country Piano Players, Dominik Hauser, Elizabeth South, [[Jim McDonough]], John Tracy, [[Mannheim Steamroller]], [[Nick Lachey]], Steven C, and [[Sue Keller]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Where Are You Christmas - Faith Hill {{!}} Cover Songs |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/where-are-you-christmas-mt0011344526/also-performed-by |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the song was performed by [[Kaitlyn Maher]] in a live show at [[The White House]], at the lighting of the [[National Christmas Tree]] on December 4, 2008, which was attended by President [[George W. Bush]].\n\nIn 2009, \"Where Are You Christmas\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Where-Are-Christmas-Hollie-Steel/dp/B002YP4ETW/ |title=Where Are You Christmas?: Hollie Steel: Music |date= |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> was covered by [[Hollie Steel]], the child soprano from ''[[Britain's Got Talent (series 3)|Britain Got Talent]]'' finals.\n\nOn October 29, 2009, Then There Were None released a cover of the Christmas single.\n\nDuring a Christmas concert in 2011, a cover of the song was performed by [[The Piano Guys]] ([[Jon Schmidt]], [[Steven Sharp Nelson]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepianoguys.com/portfolio/where-are-you-christmas-live-in-concert/ |title=ThePianoGuys.com:Where are you Christmas? (Live in concert) |publisher=ThePianoGuys.com}}</ref> featuring Jon's young daughter Sarah Schmidt.\n\nThe album version of ''[[Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas! The Musical]]'' features a bonus track of the song, performed by Tori Feinstein, who played Cindy Lou Who in a touring production of the musical.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/HOW-THE-GRINCH-STOLE-CHRISTMAS-Album-Track-List-Revealed-Out-1029-20131023|title=HOW THE GRINCH STOLE CHRISTMAS! Album Track List Revealed; Out 10/29!|date=2013-10-23|publisher=Broadway World|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\n[[Pentatonix]] covered the song for their 2018 album ''[[Christmas Is Here!]]''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Faith Hill singles}}\n\n[[Category:2000 singles]]\n[[Category:2009 singles]]\n[[Category:American Christmas songs]]\n[[Category:Faith Hill songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Paul Hunter (director)]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Will Jennings]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mariah Carey]]\n[[Category:Hollie Steel songs]]\n[[Category:Theme music]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by James Horner]]\n[[Category:2000 songs]]\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Where Are You Christmas?\n| cover      = Faith Hill - Where Are You Christmas?.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Faith Hill]]\n| album      = [[Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000 film)#Soundtrack|How the Grinch Stole Christmas ''soundtrack'']]\n| released   = {{date|2000-12-11|MDY}}\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   = 2000\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Christmas music|Christmas]]|[[Country music|country]]|[[Pop music|pop]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=4|s=07}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros. Nashville]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Mariah Carey]]|[[James Horner]]|[[Will Jennings]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Byron Gallimore]]|Faith Hill}}\n| prev_title = [[Let's Make Love (song)|Let's Make Love]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[If My Heart Had Wings]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\n\"'''Christmas, Why Can't I Find You?'''\" is a song co-written by Mariah Carey, [[James Horner]] and [[Will Jennings]] for the movie ''[[Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000 film)|How the Grinch Stole Christmas]]'' in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0170016/soundtrack|title=How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000) - Soundtracks|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2013-08-10}}</ref> In the film, it is first sung by [[Taylor Momsen]], who played [[Cindy Lou Who]].<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://est1997.com/music/where-are-you-christmas-mariah-careys-unsung-holiday-classic/|title=Where Are You Christmas? Mariah Carey's Unsung Holiday Classic|date=2017-12-17|publisher=Established in 1997|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref> \n\n[[Mariah Carey]] co-wrote a full-length version of the song with additional lyrics, renamed \"'''Where Are You Christmas?'''\", for the film's soundtrack. The song was originally recorded by Carey, but because of a [[legal case]] with her ex-husband [[Tommy Mottola]], it could not be released, so it was re-recorded and released by [[Faith Hill]].<ref name=history /> A [[CD single]] of Hill's rendition was released December 11, 2000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where Are You Christmas ? |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Where-Are-Christmas-Faith-Hill/dp/B000056WGS |website=[[Amazon UK]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> A video was released featuring Hill singing from the [[Grinch]]'s mountaintop home, interspersed with clips from the film and a cameo appearance by Momsen as Cindy Lou Who.\n\n==Composition==\n\"Where Are You Christmas?\" is a [[power ballad]] written by James Horner and Will Jennings, with additional lyrics provided by Mariah Carey.<ref name=history/> The song is composed in the key of [[B-flat major|B{{flat}} major]] and set to a slow tempo of 56 [[tempo#Beats per minute|BPM]].<ref name=\"sheet music\">{{cite web |title=Faith Hill \"Where Are You Christmas?\" Sheet Music in B{{flat}} Major |url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0038180 |publisher=[[Universal Music Publishing Group]] via Musicnotes.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> Hill's vocals range almost two octaves, from F{{sub|3}} to E{{flat}}{{sub|5}}.<ref name=\"sheet music\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nBilly Dukes of ''[[Taste of Country]]'' ranked \"Where Are You Christmas?\" at number 6 on a list of the top 50 [[country music|country]] [[Christmas song]]s, writing that the song was \"touching\" and that \"Hill performs it like a woman at the top of her game, which she certainly was.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dukes |first1=Billy |title=No. 6: Faith Hill, 'Where Are You Christmas' - Top 50 Country Christmas Songs |url=https://tasteofcountry.com/faith-hill-where-are-you-christmas-top-50-country-christmas-songs/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=[[Taste of Country]] |date=November 19, 2012}}</ref> Describing the song as underrated, Pip Ellwood-Hughes of ''Entertainment Focus'' praised Hill's vocal performance, writing that \"[she] sounds incredible as she unleashes the full range of her powerful voice.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ellwood-Hughes |first1=Pip |title=EF Country Advent Calendar Day 5: Faith Hill \u2013 Where Are You Christmas? |url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/ef-country/ef-country-advent-calendar-day-5-faith-hill-where-are-you-christmas/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=Entertainment Focus |date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nConversely, ''[[The Atlantic]]'' labelled the song as one of the top ten \"most annoying\" holiday songs. \"She sounds like a crazy person asking after an imaginary friend,\" writes Cameron Martin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Cameron |title=The 10 Most Annoying and Ubiquitous Holiday Songs |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2010/12/the-10-most-annoying-and-ubiquitous-holiday-songs/67585/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=December 7, 2010}}</ref> Steve Simels of ''[[TV Guide]]'' was critical of \"Where Are You Christmas?\" in his review of the Grinch film, writing that \"none but the thoroughly perverse of hearing should stick around for the closing credits and Faith Hill warbling\" the song.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Simels |first1=Steve |title=Dr. Seuss' How The Grinch Stole Christmas - Movie Reviews and Movie Ratings |url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/dr-seuss-how-the-grinch-stole-christmas/review/134709/ |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Where Are You Christmas?\" peaked at number 10 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart in January 2001, becoming Hill's fifth top ten single at that format.<ref name=\"adult contemporary\"/> The song experienced [[crossover music|crossover]] success at radio, peaking at number 26 on the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart and at number 40 on the [[Adult Pop Songs]] chart, in addition to reaching a peak position of 65 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In 2013, \"Where Are You Christmas?\" peaked at number 15 on the seasonal Holiday 100 chart,<ref name=\"holiday 100\"/> on which it has continued making appearances throughout the 2010s.<ref name=history/> The song has never entered the [[Canadian Hot 100]], but did reach a peak position of 38 of the [[Hot Canadian Digital Songs]] component chart in 2018.<ref name=\"canada digital\"/>\n\n\"Where Are You Christmas\" was placed seventh{{efn|At the time of the article's publication in November 2016, the song ranked at number seven with a sales figure of 897,000. With certified sales of 977,000 as of December 2018, the song should now ostensibly rank at number six ahead of \"[[Christmas Canon]]\".}} on the list of all-time [[Best-selling Christmas/holiday singles in the United States|best-selling Christmas/holiday digital singles]] in SoundScan history in  2016.<ref>{{cite web|author= Billboard Staff|date= November 25, 2016 |title= What Are the Top-Selling Holiday Songs? |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7588783/what-are-the-top-selling-christmas-music-holiday-songs |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate= December 2, 2016}}</ref> \nAs of December 2019, total digital sales of the Faith Hill recording has reached 1,002,000 downloads according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |title=Top 30 Digital Country Tracks - Pure Sales: December 9, 2019 |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2019/12/44071-top-30-digital-country-tracks-pure-sales-december-9-2019 |work=Rough Stock |date=December 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (2000-18)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada [[Hot Canadian Digital Songs|Hot Digital Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"canada digital\">{{cite web |title=Faith Hill Chart History (Hot Canadian Digital Song Sales) |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Faith-Hill/chart-history/CNS |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| 38\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch40|37|artist=Faith Hill|song=Where Are You Christmas?|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|35|artist=Faith Hill|song=Where Are You Christmas?|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|65|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardadultcontemporary|10|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019|refname=\"adult contemporary\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardadultpopsongs|40|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Holiday 100 (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"holiday 100\">{{cite web |title=Faith Hill Chart History (Holiday 100) |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Faith-Hill/chart-history/HSX |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| 15\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardcountrysongs|26|artist=Faith Hill|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}\n|}\n\n==Other versions==\n\"Where Are You Christmas?\" has been [[cover version|covered]] by a variety of artists since its release, including Ali & Theo, [[The Blenders]], Charlie Miller, The Country Piano Players, Dominik Hauser, Elizabeth South, [[Jim McDonough]], John Tracy, [[Mannheim Steamroller]], [[Nick Lachey]], Steven C, and [[Sue Keller]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Where Are You Christmas - Faith Hill {{!}} Cover Songs |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/where-are-you-christmas-mt0011344526/also-performed-by |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the song was performed  by [[Kaitlyn Maher]] in a live show at [[The White House]], at the lighting of the [[National Christmas Tree]] on December 4, 2008 which was attended by President [[George W. Bush]].\n\nIn 2009, \"Where Are You Christmas\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Where-Are-Christmas-Hollie-Steel/dp/B002YP4ETW/ |title=Where Are You Christmas?: Hollie Steel: Music |date= |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> was covered by [[Hollie Steel]], the child soprano from ''[[Britain's Got Talent (series 3)|Britain Got Talent]]'' finals.\n\nOn October 29, 2009, Then There Were None released a cover of the Christmas single.\n\nDuring a Christmas concert in 2011, a cover of the song was performed by [[The Piano Guys]] ([[Jon Schmidt]], [[Steven Sharp Nelson]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepianoguys.com/portfolio/where-are-you-christmas-live-in-concert/ |title=ThePianoGuys.com:Where are you Christmas? (Live in concert) |publisher=ThePianoGuys.com}}</ref> featuring Jon's young daughter Sarah Schmidt.\n\nThe album version of ''[[Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas! The Musical]]'' features a bonus track of the song, performed by Tori Feinstein, who played Cindy Lou Who in a touring production of the musical.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/HOW-THE-GRINCH-STOLE-CHRISTMAS-Album-Track-List-Revealed-Out-1029-20131023|title=HOW THE GRINCH STOLE CHRISTMAS! Album Track List Revealed; Out 10/29!|date=2013-10-23|publisher=Broadway World|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\n[[Pentatonix]] covered the song for their 2018 album ''[[Christmas Is Here!]]''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Faith Hill singles}}\n\n[[Category:2000 singles]]\n[[Category:2009 singles]]\n[[Category:American Christmas songs]]\n[[Category:Faith Hill songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Paul Hunter (director)]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Will Jennings]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mariah Carey]]\n[[Category:Hollie Steel songs]]\n[[Category:Theme music]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by James Horner]]\n[[Category:2000 songs]]\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n", "name_user": "Jadenpb", "label": "